Ekiti House of Assembly has passed the reviewed budget of N91.1 billion for the 2020 fiscal year. The reviewed budget was passed at a plenary, following the consideration of the report submitted by the House Committee on Finance and Appropriation. The committee chairman Mrs Olubunmi Adelugba, representing Emure Constituency, submitted the report at the plenary presided over by the Speaker, Rt. Hon, Funminiyi Afuye. Adelugba said the downward review of the 2020 budget became imperative in view of the present economic reality in the country. She added that the reviewed appropriation was inevitable in the face of the Covid-19 ravaging the whole world. “Due to the current COVID-19 pandemic which has threatened the full implementation of the State 2020 Budget as revenue from Crude oil, a major source of revenue to Ekiti has reduced. “With present economic reality, there is a need to review the 2020 budget earlier passed, ” Adelugba said. The committee’s report, according to her, was subjected to review by the Committee on Supplies. The Assembly had earlier passed the 2020 budget sum of N124.7 billion before the COVID-19 pandemic. In the reviewed appropriation bill, the recurrent expenditure was reduced to 59.1billion from the initial sum of  N71.1 billion, while capital expenditure was cut down to 32.1 billion from N53.5 billion. Responding, the Speaker, Hon Afuye said there is the need to face the reality on the ground to  ensure  government positive impact is felt, through achievable interventions and programmes at this present time. 